	Administrative penalty schemes
		Administrative penalty schemes
			The appropriate national authority for any area may by order make provisionto confer on any enforcement authority for that area the power to issuepenalty notices for offences within subsection (2).
			The offences referred to in subsection (1) are offences relating to seafishing, other than—
				an offence under section 30 of the [Fisheries Act 1981 (c.29)](/id/ukpga/1981/29?view=plain "Go to item of legislation") or any ordermade under that section;
				an offence under regulations made under section 2(2) of the [EuropeanCommunities Act 1972 (c. 68)](/id/ukpga/1972/68?view=plain "Go to item oflegislation").
			A penalty notice is a notice offering the opportunity, by payment of aspecified sum of money, to discharge any liability to be convicted of theoffence to which the notice relates.
			The provision that may be made by an order under subsection (1) includes—
				provision prescribing the offences in relation to which penalty notices maybe issued;
				provision as to circumstances in which penalty notices may be issued;
				provision as to the content and form of penalty notices;
				provision as to how the amount of any penalty that may be specified in apenalty notice is to be determined;
				provision for the issuing of guidance by the appropriate national authorityas to matters to be taken into account when making such a determination;
				provision prescribing the minimum or maximum amount of any penalty;
				provision about the payment of penalties, including provision as to theperiod within which any penalty must be paid;
				provision for and in connection with the withdrawal of penalty notices;
				provision as to circumstances in which proceedings for an offence may becommenced after the payment of a penalty in relation to that offence.
			An order under subsection (1) may apply in relation to—
				England; 
				Wales; 
				any vessels in waters within British fishery limits, other than—
				the Scottish zone,
				the Northern Ireland zone, and
				the territorial sea adjacent to the Isle of Man, Jersey and Guernsey;
				any English or Welsh fishing boats, wherever they may be.
			Her Majesty may by Order in Council provide for this section to apply, withor without modifications, to any fishing boat within subsection (7) that isoutside British fishery limits as it applies to any English or Welsh fishingboat outside those limits.
			A fishing boat is within this subsection if—
